'''Jordan's theorem''' is a statement in finite [[group theory]]. It states that if a [[primitive permutation group]] ''G'' is a [[subgroup]] of the [[symmetric group]] ''S''<sub>''n''</sub> and contains a ''p''-[[cyclic permutation|cycle]] for some [[prime number]] ''p'' < ''n'' &minus; 2, then ''G'' is either the whole symmetric group ''S''<sub>''n''</sub> or the [[alternating group]] ''A''<sub>''n''</sub>.

The statement can be generalized to the case that ''p'' is a [[prime power]].

